                    <title>This is definitely an interes…</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Comment:18541"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2012-12-06:6456126:Comment:18541</id>
                                        <updated>2012-12-06T13:00:15.660Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>Jim Hurne</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/JimHurne</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;This is definitely an interesting idea.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m not sure how I feel about this.  On the one hand, this sounds fun and innovative. On the other hand, it might re-enforce some of the conditions that make practice on the job ineffective. It is possible participants will feel some pressure to do everything on the checklist. Participants also might feel some pressure because they feel that their performance is being monitored/graded.  Usually, this type of pressure gets in the way of truly…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;This is definitely an interesting idea.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m not sure how I feel about this.  On the one hand, this sounds fun and innovative. On the other hand, it might re-enforce some of the conditions that make practice on the job ineffective. It is possible participants will feel some pressure to do everything on the checklist. Participants also might feel some pressure because they feel that their performance is being monitored/graded.  Usually, this type of pressure gets in the way of truly free, uninhibited experimentation (which we are trying to encourage).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you move forward with this, how do you plan to facilitate the day? Will you still introduce new constraints each session, or will pairs pick their own constraints based on the game sheet?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I think using this would result in a very different facilitation style than what we typically use at a coderetreat. Normally, the facilitators give a session&#039;s exercise instructions to the participants just before the session. Using this method, participants will be able to see all of the exercises and constraints up-front. I&#039;m not saying this is bad, but it is different.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also: I wouldn&#039;t list list &quot;Delete code&quot; because everyone should delete their code anyway (a critical part of the coderetreat format).  Putting it on this list suggests that it is optional, and it really shouldn&#039;t be.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anyway, this sounds like an interesting idea, and it is worth giving a try!  However, if you plan on holding more coderetreats in the next year, you might want to save this for a regular coderetreat (and not GDCR). There is already a lot going on for GDCR and my fear is that too much experimentation with the coderetreat format could become distracting or overwhelming.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Jim++&lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
